featured_reviews.review_id: Absolutely mesmerizing historical place. It needs heavy maintenance. Department of heritage should look into it. Details on the walls are indeed great skills. One can see aayat of Quran written on walls and above gates/frames. Khan Lake (khaan tllaav)behind the tomb is also very wast but no one maintains it. It was built in Sultanate era. Sultan Mohammed Begada was the one incharge 1459-1511. We saw many Different kind of Birds here.Truly a beautiful place.

I request govt to kindly look after this place and take some necessary step to maintain and enhance beauty of this place..

featured_reviews.review_id:
It is believed that Khan Talav was once a prosperous town during the Mughal period, and the remains of an ancient mosque and a well can still be found in the area.

In recent years, the government has taken several initiatives to improve the infrastructure and living conditions in Khan Talav Dholka. For example, a new water supply scheme was implemented in the village, providing access to clean drinking water to the residents.

World Heritage Site.
The approach road to the mosque is really small for 2 cars. Dholka is a very small town with a lot of mosques.
This mosque is still being used and a caretaker takes care of this place.
The compound is laden with unkept grass all over. Not very highly maintained like Jama Masjid. But still a good place to visit.
